1
00:00:05,680 --> 00:00:09,710
Clanker City! The big smoke! The city of ten thousand gears!

2
00:00:09,710 --> 00:00:14,639
One small maintenance-bot, one dream, and not so much as an oil can to my name.

3
00:00:14,639 --> 00:00:19,169
Thanks for the ride! I'll catch the return ferry once I'm rich and famous.

4
00:00:20,540 --> 00:00:23,020
...

5
00:00:23,020 --> 00:00:25,460
That clunk sounded expensive.

6
00:00:26,120 --> 00:00:28,580
That clunk sounded PERMANENT.

7
00:00:33,420 --> 00:00:36,260
WELCOME TO CLANKER CITY. POP. 8,01,1.

8
00:00:36,260 --> 00:00:40,390
Population eight-oh-one-comma-one. The punctuation died first.

9
00:00:44,760 --> 00:00:47,980
Maybe a good honest whack will fix the display.

10
00:00:48,420 --> 00:00:52,120
It rained a bolt. In this town that's basically a tip.

11
00:00:56,890 --> 00:01:01,890
One bolt. Only eight thousand and ten more and I can afford a personality upgrade.

12
00:01:07,810 --> 00:01:10,720
Official city notice, hot off the press:

13
00:01:10,720 --> 00:01:15,170
'DYNAMO MAINTENANCE: NOTHING IS WRONG. NOTHING HAS EVER BEEN WRONG.'

14
00:01:15,170 --> 00:01:18,530
'DO NOT STOCKPILE OIL. SIGNED, MAYOR PISTON.'

15
00:01:18,530 --> 00:01:23,259
The Great Dynamo powers every bot on this island. Including me, as of today.

16
00:01:23,479 --> 00:01:27,039
So that notice is the scariest thing I've ever read.

17
00:01:31,210 --> 00:01:34,140
Let me read it first. I'm a maintenance-bot, not a barbarian.

18
00:01:40,729 --> 00:01:43,130
Hello up there! Lovely evening!

19
00:01:44,450 --> 00:01:48,800
...

20
00:02:15,220 --> 00:02:19,060
A player piano, playing itself. It's missing three keys.

21
00:02:19,060 --> 00:02:22,170
...That feels thematically significant.

22
00:02:54,220 --> 00:02:58,910
I lean in casually. Extremely casually. Nobody has ever leaned this casually.

23
00:02:58,910 --> 00:03:03,890
The one in the hat says: you CLANG twice, then once, then twice, you barnacle.

24
00:03:03,890 --> 00:03:07,000
I am definitely not supposed to know that.

25
00:03:13,450 --> 00:03:15,660
Token on the rail. Game on.

26
00:03:16,350 --> 00:03:18,380
Dart one: the wall.

27
00:03:18,840 --> 00:03:21,280
Dart two: a different wall.

28
00:03:21,710 --> 00:03:25,450
Dart three is in the ocean. We're indoors. Nobody knows.

29
00:03:25,660 --> 00:03:31,440
Flange is laughing so hard he goes for the showboat finish: three darts, one throw, behind the back.

30
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:36,970
His shoulder servo overheats with a noise like bacon achieving liftoff.

31
00:03:36,970 --> 00:03:41,610
House rules: the overheated party forfeits the wager. The oil can is mine.

32
00:03:41,610 --> 00:03:46,010
Losing this badly took real skill. Nobody will ever believe that.

33
00:04:03,220 --> 00:04:05,880
Her joints are dry as a tax form. She needs oil before she'll move that crate.

34
00:04:23,900 --> 00:04:27,210
It's twenty feet up. My arms are stock parts.

35
00:04:27,210 --> 00:04:32,320
Betty could set it down, if anyone gave her a drink of oil.

36
00:04:32,320 --> 00:04:36,359
The lid argues. I argue back with a plank.

37
00:05:04,840 --> 00:05:09,090
Rivet's the name, he says. Knows everything. First fact's free:

38
00:05:09,090 --> 00:05:14,690
The funicular to Midtown takes ten bolts. Exact change. Gates can count — it's all they do.

39
00:05:14,909 --> 00:05:20,060
Second fact costs a bolt. He can see I don't have one. He mentions that for free too.

40
00:05:20,060 --> 00:05:26,770
Third freebie, out of pity: the harbor keeps everything this town drops, and that dumpster is — legally — his.

41
00:05:32,950 --> 00:05:37,599
Someone sprayed DYNAMO IS FINE. Crossed out. Under it, smaller: IT IS NOT.

42
00:05:37,599 --> 00:05:41,680
Under that, very small: NO REFUNDS. The whole town, one wall.

43
00:05:46,330 --> 00:05:48,120
Knock knock.

44
00:05:48,120 --> 00:05:53,950
The slot opens. The same eye as the tavern. 'This is the BACK back door. STILL Act Three, buddy.'

45
00:05:53,950 --> 00:05:57,560
This organization has remarkable message discipline.

46
00:06:02,630 --> 00:06:08,080
Inside: one rubber duck, seized. One manual for a better game. And a magnet on a string.

47
00:06:08,080 --> 00:06:13,210
In a town held together by bolts, a magnet on a string is a license to print money.

48
00:06:25,080 --> 00:06:29,549
My fingers are factory-standard. I'd need something magnetic. On a string.

49
00:06:51,280 --> 00:06:56,169
Rivet's the name, he says. Knows everything. First fact's free:

50
00:06:56,380 --> 00:07:02,370
The funicular to Midtown takes ten bolts. Exact change. Gates can count — it's all they do.

51
00:07:02,370 --> 00:07:08,580
Second fact costs a bolt. He can see I don't have one. He mentions that for free too.

52
00:07:08,580 --> 00:07:11,930
Third freebie, out of pity: the harbor keeps everything this town drops, and that dumpster is — legally — his.

53
00:07:11,930 --> 00:07:16,789
Nine bolts, I tell him. He appraises my pockets from four feet away. Correctly.

54
00:07:16,789 --> 00:07:21,080
He proposes a riddle duel. His bolt against my official city notice. The alley has rules, apparently.

55
00:07:26,419 --> 00:07:31,549
Ten bolts in the hopper. It counts them twice. Trust died in this town years ago.

56
00:07:32,010 --> 00:07:37,380
The gate ratchets up, and a little brass car rolls down to meet me, lit up like a promise.

57
00:07:37,599 --> 00:07:40,520
Act Two. I can hear the neon from here.

58
00:07:44,740 --> 00:07:49,680
Gate's open, car's lit. Midtown keeps glittering like it doesn't know I'm coming.

59
00:07:49,680 --> 00:07:53,919
Act Two will still be uptown tomorrow. Probably. If the Dynamo holds.

60
00:08:00,010 --> 00:08:06,299
Ten bolts in the hopper. It counts them twice. Trust died in this town years ago.

61
00:08:06,299 --> 00:08:11,030
The gate ratchets up, and a little brass car rolls down to meet me, lit up like a promise.

62
00:08:11,030 --> 00:08:15,900
Act Two. I can hear the neon from here.

63
00:08:15,900 --> 00:08:18,340
The fare box wants ten bolts. I have pockets, and ambition.

64
00:08:24,440 --> 00:08:29,630
Talent night, tonight, he says. Grand prize: an oil voucher and a backstage pass.

65
00:08:29,630 --> 00:08:35,569
Backstage. Where Madame Voltina reads fortunes. And guards... things. He doesn't say what things.

66
00:08:35,569 --> 00:08:40,770
Sign-up needs a stage name and an act. I have a name, and a key the size of my forearm.

67
00:08:40,770 --> 00:08:44,110
He says, quote, that's more act than most.

68
00:08:49,890 --> 00:08:53,699
The Great Dynamo, up the hill, behind a fence with opinions.

69
00:08:53,920 --> 00:08:59,100
Every bot on this island runs on that hum. Including me. The hum is flat by half a step.

70
00:08:59,319 --> 00:09:04,230
Half a step doesn't sound like much. Neither does a clunk, until it's PERMANENT.

71
00:09:08,920 --> 00:09:12,990
City Hall. The banner says NOTHING IS WRONG. It's brand new.

72
00:09:12,990 --> 00:09:17,460
They replaced the old banner. The old one said the same thing, smaller.

73
00:09:21,840 --> 00:09:26,569
An aide opens the door exactly nine degrees. The Mayor is not seeing anyone.

74
00:09:26,569 --> 00:09:29,699
Especially, he adds, anyone holding paper.

75
00:09:58,980 --> 00:10:02,319
There it is. SPROCKET. On a marquee. In lights.

76
00:10:02,319 --> 00:10:06,090
Two of the bulbs are out. It still feels like destiny.

77
00:10:06,090 --> 00:10:10,300
Talent night. Tonight. No pressure. The marquee is the pressure.

